A sports psychology professor, Dr. Smith, is conducting a study on the performance of a basketball team during different periods of a game. She collects data on the number of successful shots made by the team during four quarters of a game. She wants to identify if there are any significant differences in the team's performance during these periods.

Dr. Smith uses a mathematical model to represent the performance as a 4x4 matrix A, where each entry a_ij represents the number of successful shots made in the i-th quarter against the j-th quarter of their opponents. 

Matrix A is given as follows:

A = [a_11, a_12, a_13, a_14;
     a_21, a_22, a_23, a_24;
     a_31, a_32, a_33, a_34;
     a_41, a_42, a_43, a_44]

She then calculates the eigenvalues of this matrix. 

The problem is to find the condition on the entries a_ij of the matrix A for which all eigenvalues of the matrix A are real numbers.
